k only","Laterally flexes neck without rotation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen the sternocleidomastoid contracts on one side, it produces \u003Cstrong\u003Erotation of the head to the opposite side with neck flexion\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs because the muscle passes obliquely from its inferior attachments on the sternum and clavicle to its superior attachment on the mastoid process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotates head towards same side\u003C/strong\u003E - The muscle rotates the head to the contralateral (opposite) side\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERotates head to opposite side with neck extension\u003C/strong\u003E - The muscle produces flexion, not extension, along with contralateral rotation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtends neck only\u003C/strong\u003E - The muscle flexes rather than extends the neck, and also produces rotation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaterally flexes neck without rotation\u003C/strong\u003E - While some lateral flexion occurs, rotation is a key component of the movement\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen both sternocleidomastoid muscles contract simultaneously, they flex the neck. The muscle is innervated by the accessory nerve (cranial nerve XI) and receives proprioceptive innervation from the second and third cervical spinal nerves.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The sternocleidomastoid muscle has two heads of origin: the sternal head from the manubrium and the clavicular head from the medial third of the clavicle","The sternocleidomastoid muscle inserts into the mastoid process of the temporal bone and superior nuchal line of the occipital bone","Unilateral contraction of the sternocleidomastoid rotates the head to the opposite side and flexes the neck"],"references":["Netter 